{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015sFiBCie9KDdhxG9qctE5r","type":"tool_result","content":"   130→\n   131→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   134→\n   135→## Host Workflow Example\n   136→\n   137→```\n   138→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   139→workflow \"main\" {\n   140→  step prepare-prompt {\n   141→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   142→    results = [success, fail]\n   143→  }\n   144→\n   145→  step develop {\n   146→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   147→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   148→    results       = [success, fail]\n   149→  }\n   150→\n   151→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   152→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   153→  develop:success        -> done\n   154→  develop:fail           -> done\n   155→}\n   156→```\n   157→\n   158→The `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n   159→`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\n   160→completes.\n   161→\n   162→## Execution Model\n   163→\n   164→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   165→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   166→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   167→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   168→\n   169→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   170→steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   171→standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   172→etc.) are injected into each step.\n   173→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3fb2401a-6b6a-4fd9-9eca-7aeee6bcc4bd","uuid":"1edc769d-b8cb-4a51-94da-8c86abcdc3f4","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\ncompletes.\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\nsteps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\nstandard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\netc.) are injected into each step.\n","numLines":44,"startLine":130,"totalLines":173}}}
